//axhob_operation
{rbtgo_ark_graft}

NOTE: This operation grafts a locally-built container image into
{rbtgi_repository}
via native docker/podman push.
No Cloud Build involvement in the image push — the image is already built on the local workstation.
No crane dependency — docker tag + docker push is sufficient for locally-present images.
No dirty-tree guard — git state is irrelevant to an already-built container.

NOTE: The name "graft" comes from botanical grafting — foreign material spliced onto rootstock.
The graft may take or may not.
The metaphor fits the trust posture: grafted images have no provenance chain and receive a GRAFTED verdict from
{rbtgo_ark_vouch}.

NOTE: Graft uses whatever container runtime the `docker` command resolves to in PATH, matching other {rbtr_director}-side operations.
No separate regime variable governs runtime selection for graft.

NOTE: *Universal reliquary precondition*. Every ordain-path vessel — conjure, bind, and graft — must have `RBRV_RELIQUARY` non-empty before this operation runs. Graft's about+vouch combined Cloud Build job consumes reliquary tool images (gcloud, docker, alpine, syft) just like conjure and bind; the registry preflight enforces this before submission.

The
{rbtr_director}
grafts an image:

//axhopt_typed_parameter
{rbtga_ark}
. *Validate Input Parameters*:
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel provided as first argument
.. {rbbc_require}
local image reference provided as second argument (or defaulted from {rbrv_graft_image})
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel mode is {rbrv_vessel_mode_graft}

//axhos_step
. *Load Vessel Configuration*:
.. Source vessel configuration from `rbrv.env`
.. {rbbc_store}
`«VESSEL_SIGIL»` from {rbrv_sigil}
.. {rbbc_store}
`«VESSEL_MODE»` from {rbrv_vessel_mode}
.. {rbbc_require}
`«VESSEL_MODE»` is `graft`

//axhos_step
. *Verify Local Image Exists*:
.. {rbbc_call}
`docker image inspect «LOCAL_IMAGE_REF»` (or podman equivalent)
.. {rbbc_require}
image exists in local container runtime
.. {rbbc_store}
`«LOCAL_DIGEST»` from local image inspect
.. {rbbc_store}
`«LOCAL_PLATFORMS»` from local image manifest (typically single-platform for local builds)

//axhos_step
. *Authenticate as
{rbtr_director}*:
.. Execute
{rbtoe_director_authenticate}
.. {rbbc_store}
`«DIRECTOR_TOKEN»` for subsequent API calls

//axhos_step
. *Construct Hallmark*:
.. {rbbc_call}
query local container runtime for image creation timestamp via `docker image inspect` (the `Created` field — OCI Image Configuration spec, exposed at `.Created` by both docker and podman)
.. {rbbc_store}
`«IMAGE_CREATED»` as the image's creation timestamp, converted to `YYMMDDHHMMSS` format
.. {rbbc_store}
`«PUSH_TIMESTAMP»` as current UTC time (`YYMMDDHHMMSS`)
.. {rbbc_store}
`«HALLMARK»` as `g«IMAGE_CREATED»-r«PUSH_TIMESTAMP»`
.. T1 encodes when the image was created (a fact about the artifact); T2 encodes when it was pushed to GAR
.. NOTE: The `created` field may be `1970-01-01T00:00:00Z` for reproducible builds. This produces `g700101000000-r...` — a true statement about the image, not an error.

//axhos_step
. *Tag and Push Image*:
.. {rbbc_call}
`docker login` to GAR registry with director credentials
.. {rbbc_store}
`«REGISTRY_TAG»` as `«GAR_HOST»/«GAR_PATH»/{gar_hallmarks_namespace}/«HALLMARK»/image:«HALLMARK»`
.. {rbbc_call}
`docker tag «LOCAL_IMAGE_REF» «REGISTRY_TAG»`
.. {rbbc_call}
`docker push «REGISTRY_TAG»`
.. {rbbc_require}
push succeeds

//axhoot_typed_output
{rbtga_ark_image}

//axhoot_typed_output axd_fact
{rbf_fact_hallmark}
The full
{rbtga_hallmark}
string.

//axhoot_typed_output axd_fact
{rbf_fact_build_id}
Empty for graft — no
{gcb_build}
involvement in image push.
Written for uniform fact coverage.

//axhoot_typed_output axd_fact
{rbf_fact_gar_root}
{gar_service}
registry prefix.
Composable with
{rbf_fact_ark_stem}
for full artifact references.

//axhoot_typed_output axd_fact
{rbf_fact_ark_stem}
The hallmark subtree prefix `{gar_hallmarks_namespace}/«HALLMARK»`.
Composable with basename (`image`, `about`, `vouch`, etc.) and the `:«HALLMARK»` tag for full artifact references.

//axhoot_typed_output axd_fact
{rbf_fact_ark_yield}
Single-platform
{rbtga_ark_image}
reference.
One fact file (graft is single-platform only).

. *Display Results*:
.. {rbbc_show}
graft complete with hallmark tag
.. {rbbc_show}
local image reference, registry tag, digest

//axhoc_completion
Successful execution pushes the locally-built image to
{rbtgi_repository}
tagged as `{gar_hallmarks_namespace}/«HALLMARK»/image:«HALLMARK»` within the hallmark subtree.
The graft operation returns `«HALLMARK»` to {rbtgo_ark_ordain}, which chains the subsequent pipeline stages automatically:
{rbtgo_ark_about} and {rbtgo_ark_vouch} in a single combined `builds.create` job (about steps followed by vouch steps) to assemble metadata and record the GRAFTED verdict.
+
*No SLSA provenance*: Grafted images have no Cloud Build provenance.
The {rbtgo_ark_vouch} pipeline records a GRAFTED verdict, explicitly marking the absence of a provenance chain.
This is a deliberate trust boundary — grafted images are accepted into the system but carry less attestation than conjured images.
+
*Push atomicity*: `docker push` is atomic per manifest — a failed push (network timeout, authentication expiry) leaves no partial state in GAR.
The director can safely retry without cleanup.
+
*Single-platform only*: Graft is specified for single-platform images only.
`docker push` of a locally-present image pushes a single manifest.
The about pipeline's platform discovery step handles this correctly, producing a single-platform `about` basename under the hallmark subtree.
Multi-platform graft is not currently specified — `buildx --load` only loads one platform into the local daemon, so true multi-platform local images would require a different push mechanism.

//axhob_operation
{rbtgo_ark_enshrine}

NOTE: This operation enshrines upstream base images into
{gar_service}
as content-addressed, human-readable anchors.
The
{rbtr_director}
submits a Cloud Build job that copies each declared
{rbrv_image_origin}
from its upstream registry to GAR using
the reliquary skopeo image
(`skopeo copy --all`), preserving the manifest list and all per-platform manifests for multi-platform images.
The locator results are returned via `buildStepOutputs` and
{rbrv_image_anchor}
is then written back to the vessel regime locally as a
{rbst_locator}.

NOTE: This operation is a pure mirror.
Every call inspects current upstream for each declared
{rbrv_image_origin}
, computes the content-addressed locator from the live manifest digest, copies the image into
{gar_service}
, and writes the resulting
{rbst_locator}
into the vessel's
{rbrv_image_anchor}
— overwriting whatever was previously committed there.
The
{rbrv_image_anchor}
is a derived artifact of this operation, not an operator-set pin.
Re-runs are idempotent with respect to upstream state, not with respect to the file's prior contents — when upstream rotates, the next call writes a different locator and that is the operation surfacing the change, not a fault.

NOTE: Vessels whose
{rbrv_image_anchor}
is written by an upstream procedure as a hallmark-pin (e.g., the airgap-bottle pointing at the just-ordained forge image via `{gar_hallmarks_namespace}/«HALLMARK»/«BASENAME»:«HALLMARK»`) do not invoke this operation.
The orchestrating procedure (handbook step or onboarding-sequence fixture) writes the locator directly;
{rbtgo_ark_conjure}
resolves it at build time.
The hallmark's existence in
{gar_service}
is established by the producer's
{rbtgo_ark_ordain}
success, not by a separate validation step here.

NOTE: Enshrine is a pre-build preparation step.
It must be run before
{rbtgo_ark_conjure}
when anchored base images are desired.
Conjure works without anchors (passing ORIGIN through), but anchored images provide reproducibility and air-gap readiness.

NOTE: Enshrine runs on Cloud Build, not the Director's workstation.
No local skopeo installation is required.
The GCB step uses Mason SA ambient credentials via the metadata server for GAR writes.

NOTE: The enshrine Cloud Build job carries the {rbsk_in_pool_preflight} as its step 0, ahead of the skopeo copy. Enshrine passes empty locator substitutions — enshrine's purpose is to create anchors, so pre-validating them would be circular.

The enshrine operation:

//axhopt_typed_parameter
{rbrv_sigil}
. *Validate Input Parameters*:
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel provided as first argument
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel declares at least one upstream base-image slot — that is, at least one of slots 1-3 has
{rbrv_image_origin}
populated.
{rbrv_image_anchor}
is computed by this operation; an ANCHOR-only slot is not a valid input shape
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel mode is `conjure` (`RBRV_VESSEL_MODE`)
.. {rbbc_require}
reliquary tool images exist in GAR (HEAD check on `docker:latest` canary)

//axhos_step
. *Submit Enshrine Cloud Build Job*:
.. Compose `builds.create` JSON with:
... Single step using
the reliquary skopeo image
as the builder image (script: `rbgje01-enshrine-copy.sh`)
... `_RBGE_*` substitutions: `_RBGE_GAR_HOST`, `_RBGE_GAR_PATH`, `_RBGE_IMAGE_n_ORIGIN` (n = 1, 2, 3; empty for unused slots). Base images are stored in the shared `{gar_enshrines_namespace}/` namespace, with each anchor as a peer package (`{gar_enshrines_namespace}/«ANCHOR»:«ANCHOR»`), not per-vessel.
... Mason SA, private pool, timeout
.. Submit via `builds.create` and wait for completion
.. The GCB step, for each non-empty ORIGIN slot:
... Fetches the raw upstream manifest (`skopeo inspect --raw`) and computes its sha256 digest (`sha256sum` of the raw manifest bytes)
... {rbbc_store}
`<<DIGEST>>` -- the sha256 digest of the upstream manifest (manifest list digest for multi-platform images, single manifest digest for single-platform images)
... Constructs anchor: sanitize full origin string (`:` `/` replaced with `-`), append first 10 hex chars of sha256 digest
... Example: `python:3.11-slim` with `sha256:abc123def4...` yields anchor `python-3.11-slim-abc123def4`
... Composes the
{rbst_locator}
as `{gar_enshrines_namespace}/«ANCHOR»:«ANCHOR»` (e.g., `{gar_enshrines_namespace}/python-3.11-slim-abc123def4:python-3.11-slim-abc123def4`)
... Copies upstream image into the shared `{gar_enshrines_namespace}/` namespace in GAR as a peer package at `{gar_enshrines_namespace}/«ANCHOR»:«ANCHOR»` using `skopeo copy --all`, transferring the manifest list and all per-platform manifests atomically. Each anchor is its own package under the namespace — the path segment carries the anchor identity, and the tag redundantly restates it so divergence is a visible bug. The anchor is vessel-independent — multiple vessels sharing the same base image origin share one enshrined package.
... {rbbc_require}
copy succeeds -- the locator now resolves to a permanent, content-addressed reference in
{gar_service}
containing all upstream platforms
... Single-platform upstream images are handled identically -- `skopeo copy --all` is a no-op on the platform dimension when only one platform exists
.. Writes JSON locator results to `/builder/outputs/output` (returned as `buildStepOutputs`); each slot's `anchor` field carries the full locator string

//axhos_step
. *Extract Locators and Write Regime*:
.. Read `buildStepOutputs[0]` from the completed build result (base64-decoded JSON)
.. For each slot present in the result:
... Write locator string to `RBRV_IMAGE_n_ANCHOR` in the vessel's `rbrv.env`, overwriting any prior value

//axhoot_typed_output
{rbrv_image_anchor}
Per-slot locator string written to the vessel regime.

//axhoc_completion
Successful execution produces anchored base image references in
{gar_service}
(with all upstream platforms preserved) and updates the vessel regime with
{rbrv_image_anchor}
values.
The vessel is now ready for reproducible
{rbtgo_ark_conjure}
builds using GAR-mirrored base images.
Multi-platform conjure vessels pull the correct platform from the anchored manifest list automatically.
Re-running enshrine with the same
{rbrv_image_origin}
but a different upstream digest produces a new locator (upstream image was updated).
Re-running with the same digest is idempotent.

//axhob_operation
{rbtgo_depot_inscribe}

NOTE: This operation mirrors upstream tool images (gcloud, docker, alpine, syft, binfmt, skopeo) into a datestamped GAR namespace within the
{rbtgi_depot}.
The resulting reliquary is referenced by vessel regimes via `RBRV_RELIQUARY` and consumed at conjure time as the toolchain source.

